# Module Five: RIP Routing & NAT Configuration
**CYB-210 | Computer Networking**

## Objective
Configure a router via CLI to implement RIP (Routing Information Protocol) dynamic routing and NAT on a restructured network, then verify full connectivity with ping tests.

---

## Part I — IP Configuration & Connectivity Verification
Accessed three admin PCs (PC1_Admin, PC2_Admin, PC3_Admin) and updated IP addresses and default gateways using the IP Configuration application. Configured the Admin_Printer default gateway via the Config tab.

**Connectivity test:** Initiated a ping from PC1_Admin to Server_Main (192.168.20.100).
- First request: timed out (expected — ARP resolution)
- Subsequent three replies: ✅ successful

Applied same process to the Student network segment and confirmed connectivity.

---

## Part II — RIP Dynamic Routing Configuration

### Steps completed via Router CLI:
```
Router> enable
Router# configure terminal

! Remove outdated RIP entries
Router(config)# router rip
Router(config-router)# no network 192.168.6.0
Router(config-router)# no network 192.168.9.0

! Assign new IPs to interfaces
Router(config)# interface FastEthernet0/0
Router(config-if)# ip address 192.168.12.1 255.255.255.0

Router(config)# interface FastEthernet1/0
Router(config-if)# ip address 192.168.20.1 255.255.255.0

! Add new networks to RIP
Router(config)# router rip
Router(config-router)# network 192.168.12.0
Router(config-router)# network 192.168.20.0
Router(config-router)# exit
```

**Troubleshooting note:** Encountered an error with interface naming. Used `show ip interface brief` to identify the correct interface names — a key diagnostic command for any network engineer.

---

## Part III — NAT Configuration

```
! Assign inside/outside interfaces
Router(config)# interface FastEthernet0/0
Router(config-if)# ip nat inside

Router(config)# interface FastEthernet1/0
Router(config-if)# ip nat outside

! Static NAT rule
Router(config)# ip nat inside source static 192.168.12.1 [outside-ip]
```

**Result:** Internal IP (192.168.12.1) successfully mapped to external address. Devices on the internal network can communicate externally while their true IPs remain hidden.

